text.tspan: Mercury is the closest planet to the Sun and
due to its proximity it is not easily seen except
during twilight. For every two orbits of the Sun,
Mercury completes three rotations about its
axis and up until 1965 it was thought that the
same side of Mercury constantly faced the Sun.
Thirteen times a century Mercury can be
observed from the Earth passing across the
face of the Sun in an event called a transit, the
next will occur on the 9th May 2016.
